<Window x:Class="SnakesAndLadders.RulesWindow"
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        Title="Game Rules"
        Width="752" Height="570"
        WindowStartupLocation="CenterScreen"
        ResizeMode="NoResize">

    <Border Padding="20" Background="White">
        <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="16">
    <Bold>RULES</Bold>
    <LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    This is digital Snakes and Ladders for 2 players.
    <LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    • Each player has their <Bold>own board</Bold><LineBreak/>
    • Players take turns to roll the die by clicking the <Bold>Go</Bold> buttons and then selecting a counter<LineBreak/>
    • If you have <Bold>tokens</Bold>, you may move <Bold>either</Bold> counter<LineBreak/>
    • If you have no tokens, you may only move your <Bold>own</Bold> counter<LineBreak/>
    • Use tokens wisely for <Bold>strategic advantage</Bold>!<LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    • Landing at the <Bold>bottom of a ladder</Bold> moves the counter to the top<LineBreak/>
    • Landing on the <Bold>head of a snake</Bold> moves the counter to the bottom<LineBreak/>
    • Landing on the <Bold>blue arrows</Bold> triggers a transition to another board<LineBreak/>
    • Sometimes landing on a square will trigger a <Bold>sound bite</Bold><LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    • You win by finishing <Bold>exactly on square 100</Bold> on any board<LineBreak/>
    • If a roll takes you beyond 100, the <Bold>excess counts back</Bold><LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    • There are up to <Bold>8 boards</Bold> that may be revealed in a game<LineBreak/>
    • In <Bold>Upside Down World</Bold>, players move <Bold>up snakes</Bold> and <Bold>down ladders</Bold>!<LineBreak/>
    • In <Bold>Chaos Zone</Bold>, board elements are hidden and counters move <Bold>unexpectedly</Bold><LineBreak/><LineBreak/>

    <Bold>The most important rule is to HAVE FUN!</Bold>
            </TextBlock>

        </ScrollViewer>
    </Border>
</Window>
